    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Polite Ordering with 'Ja bih...' & The Accusative Case",
      "explanation": "To politely order food or drink in Serbian, use the phrase 'Ja bih...' (Ја бих...) meaning 'I would like...'. This is the conditional form of the verb 'biti' (to be/to want) and is the most common polite way to request something. When you use 'Ja bih' followed by a noun, that noun must be in the accusative case, which is the grammatical case for direct objects. For feminine nouns ending in '-a', the accusative changes '-a' to '-u': 'kafa' becomes 'kafu', 'voda' becomes 'vodu', 'salata' becomes 'salatu'. Masculine inanimate nouns stay the same in accusative: 'hleb' stays 'hleb', 'sir' stays 'sir'. Neuter nouns also stay the same: 'pivo' stays 'pivo', 'vino' stays 'vino'. You can also simply say 'Može jedna kafa' (Can I get a coffee) for a more casual approach.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "I would like a coffee.",
          "target_alt": "Ја бих кафу.",
          "target_primary": "Ja bih kafu."
        },
        {
          "english": "I would like water.",
          "target_alt": "Ја бих воду.",
          "target_primary": "Ja bih vodu."
        },
        {
          "english": "I would like bread.",
          "target_alt": "Ја бих хлеб.",
          "target_primary": "Ja bih hleb."
        },
        {
          "english": "I would like a beer.",
          "target_alt": "Ја бих пиво.",
          "target_primary": "Ja bih pivo."
        },
        {
